pain_points_original.title: Lagging Lawyer Productivity & Workflow Inefficiency
pain_points_original.description: Current legal practice workflows involve significant manual effort in high-volume tasks like document review, summarisation, and drafting, limiting the capacity of 570+ lawyers and impacting efficiency.

pain_points_original.title: Risk of Falling Behind on Advanced "Agentic AI"
pain_points_original.description: AGS foresees the limits of current generative AI and seeks to leverage next-generation 'agentic AI' for autonomous, multi-step task execution to maintain a strategic advantage in the legal sector.

pain_points_original.title: Critical Data Security & Sovereignty Constraints
pain_points_original.description: As the government's legal provider, AGS must ensure any AI solution meets PROTECTED-level security (IRAP certified) and Australian data sovereignty rules, presenting a major strategic adoption barrier.
source_references: Attachment A - AGD Non-Functional Requirements.pdf page 5

pain_points_original.title: Need for Explainable and Ethical AI Governance
pain_points_original.description: For a legal authority, AI tools cannot be a 'black box'. Outputs must be transparent, explainable, and ethically sound to maintain legal integrity, presenting a core strategic challenge for adoption.
source_references: Attachment A - AGD Non-Functional Requirements.pdf page 3

pain_points_original.title: Inefficient Knowledge Management & Discovery
pain_points_original.description: AGS struggles to efficiently find and leverage its vast internal knowledge base of precedents and legal opinions, impacting service consistency and the speed of research and advice formulation.
